{In Vienna, Mandler met many great chess players and this coproduction with
Imre König is among my favorites for its fourfold echo, light setting and
ultimately humor, showing that already in January 1924 Mandler's talent could
get him a chuckle. White to move and win.} 1. f7 $1 ({White can try other
ideas, and while Mandler's defenses aren't the only ones, ultimately they
easily draw.} 1. Rf2 $2 Rf3 $1 ({Among this study's more extended analysis, i.
e. not written by Mandler or reprints but if readers analyze the position, the
pawn sacrifice on a2 is also often working.} 1... a2 2. f7 Rbc3+ $1 3. Rxc3
Rxc3+ 4. Kb4 Rc8 $11) 2. Rcf1 Rxf2 3. Rxf2 Rb2 4. Rf1 a2 5. f7 Rb8 $11) (1. Rg2
$2 Rh3 2. Rf1 Rbf3 $1 3. Rgf2 Rxf2 4. Rxf2 a2 $1 $11) 1... Kg7 2. f8=Q+ $1 Kxf8
3. Rf1+ Kg7 $1 ({Other main variation:} 3... Rf3 4. Ref2 Rbc3+ 5. Kb4 Rb3+ 6.
Ka4 $18) ({Other main variation:} 3... Ke8 4. Rfe1 Rbc3+ 5. Kb4 Rb3+ 6. Ka4 $18
) (3... Ke7 4. Rfe1 $1 Rbc3+ 5. Kb4 Rb3+ 6. Ka4) 4. Rg2+ Kh6 ({Other main
variation (not given as main in the original source apparently):} 4... Rg3 5.
Rfg1 $18) 5. Rh1+ Rh3 6. Rgh2 $1 Rbc3+ 7. Kb4 Rb3+ 8. Ka4 $18 {and after being
pinned on e3, f3, g3 or h3 the rook can't defend his brother while saving
himself. A very curious position where White wins an endgame that materially
should otherwise be a dead draw.} 1-0

