{I would like to take this November 1967 study from "TfS", as it is commonly
abbreviated, to show how an incorrectness and correction of an idea can spawn
something new. Mandler's original solution and the "cook" (unintended solution)
are shown here, the correction split this study into two positions to show
both solutions. Another idea would have been to keep the position but make the
stipulation into "Draw. 2 solutions", although such multiple solutions are
usually used in helpmates, rarely in directmate problems and almost never in
endgame studies. White is to move and draw.} 1. Na5+ ({The unintended solution
runs} 1. Nd6+ $1 R5b7 2. Ka5 Ka7 3. Bxb7 Bxb7 4. Nb5+ Ka8 5. Nc7+ $11) 1...
R5b7 2. Ka3 Ka7 3. Bxb7 Bxb7 4. Nc6+ Bxc6 {with a stalemate. Note that for the
sake of this article, this study and its twin correction will be treated as a
single study, so the higher number of studies this month is mostly due to this.
} 1/2-1/2

