{Before we get to the fun conclusion, we will show the entire depth of
Mandler's ideas in a simple-looking pawn endgame. Readers are welcome to play
through all the variations, or just skip them and only watch the main
variation of this study if they feel intimidated. White is to move and win.} 1.
Ka7 ({The obvious move does not win:} 1. Kc8 $2 d6 2. Kd8 Kb7 3. d5 ({The
opposition or rather White being unable to maintain it is important also:} 3.
Kd7 Kb6 $11) (3. Ke7 Ka6 $11) 3... Kb6 4. Kd7 Kb7 5. Ke6 Kb6 6. Kxf5 Kc5 7.
Kxf4 Kxc4 {and it looks completely won for White, but...} 8. Ke4 Kc5 9. f4 c6
$11) 1... Kd6 ({A symphony of opposition and countersquares runs after} 1... d6
2. Ka6 (2. Ka8 $2 Kb6 3. Kb8 c6 4. Kc8 Ka5 5. Kc7 Kb4 6. Kxc6 Kxc4 7. d5 Kd4 8.
Kxd6 Ke3 9. Ke5 Kxf3 10. d6 Kg3 $11) 2... Kd7 3. Kb7 Kd8 4. Ka7 Ke7 $1 (4...
Kd7 5. Kb8 $18) (4... Kc8 5. Ka8 $18) (4... Ke8 5. c5 $18) 5. Ka8 Ke6 (5... Kd7
6. Kb8 $1 Kc6 7. Kc8 Kb6 8. Kd7 $1 (8. d5 $2 c6 9. Kd7 cxd5 10. cxd5 Kc5 11.
Ke6 Kd4 12. Kxd6 Ke3 13. Ke5 Kxf3 14. d6 Kg3 15. d7 f3 16. d8=Q f2 $11 {and
despite the extra pawn for Black, White can't win as he needs the checking
field g4. This is an interesting position to show to pupils in a chess club
when they know the h-/f-pawn draw vs. queen.}) 8... Kb7 9. c5 dxc5 10. dxc5 c6
11. Kd6 $18) (5... Ke8 6. c5 $18) (5... Kd8 6. Kb7 $18) (5... Kf6 6. Kb7 c5 7.
d5 Ke5 8. Kc6 Kd4 9. Kxd6 Kxc4 (9... Ke3 10. Kxc5 $18) 10. Kc6 $18) 6. Kb7 Kd7
7. c5 dxc5 8. dxc5 c6 (8... Kd8 9. c6 $18) 9. Kb6 $18) (1... d5 2. c5 Kb5 3.
Kb7 Kc4 4. Kxc7 Kxd4 5. Kd6 ({Of course White can also reverse the move order,
so here or in the previous move pushing the pawn also wins:} 5. c6 $18) 5...
Ke3 6. c6 Kxf3 7. Ke5 ({I leave it as a small exercise to readers to figure
