{For our last study or rather two studies, we show side by side two bishop
endgames from the same era. Mandler used the same trick in both studies but it
wind only in one while in the other one there is just a draw. So here White is
to move and draw.} 1. c5 (1. Kxb6 $2 Bd3 $1 {There is the trick. Or rather it
will be in the fourth move of the main variation, but here it would be if
White does not anticipate it.} 2. c5 Bxe2 3. c6 Bg4 $19) 1... bxc5 2. Kb6 c4 $1
3. Bxc4 a3 4. Kc5 Bd3 $3 {An incredible move. And yet White can draw.} 5. Ba2
$1 Bxe2 6. Kd4 Bc4 $1 {Often in endgames with this material just sacrificing
the bishop wins. Here the bad luck of remaining with the wrong pawn prevents
it.} 7. Kxe3 $1 Bxa2 8. Kd2 (8. Kd3 $2 Bb3 $19) 8... Bb3 9. Kc1 Ba2 10. Kc2 $11
{and the black king is just too far away to protect b4 before White arrives
there.} 1/2-1/2

